The 2014 Indian general elections were held in nine phases from April 7 to May 12, 2014. The main contenders were the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP), led by Narendra Modi, and the Indian National Congress (INC), led by Rahul Gandhi. The BJP secured a landslide victory, winning 282 out of 545 seats in the Lok Sabha (the lower house of India's Parliament). Narendra Modi became the Prime Minister, and the BJP-led National Democratic Alliance (NDA) obtained a clear majority with 336 seats. The INC and other opposition parties faced significant losses, marking a decisive shift in political power. The 2014 elections were notable for the BJP's strong mandate, reflecting widespread dissatisfaction with the previous government and an endorsement of Modi's leadership.
